"A very good morning to you, Mr. President. I trust I'm not imposing by arriving ahead of schedule?"

As the morning sun streamed through the window of the Presidential Office, an imminent meeting loomed on my agenda. In a quarter of an hour, I was set to discuss the Energy Protection Act of 1932 with Ministers Graf, Holl, and Wisci.

LineNo: 2623695,

Player: Given the serious topic we're addr...
en


"Given the serious topic we're addressing, an early start might be just what we need."

en


I gestured towards the seat.

LineNo: 2623905,

Narrator: I was sipping my morning coffee and...
en


I was sipping my morning coffee and enjoying a quiet moment of solitude when Deivid arrived, characteristically early.

LineNo: 2624007,

Player: Not at all, Deivid. On the contrar...
en


"Not at all, Deivid. On the contrary, we've now got an extra few minutes to strategize before the meeting."

LineNo: 2624109,

Narrator: The recent abrogation in the Grand...
en


The recent abrogation in the Grand National Assembly, coupled with ongoing dialogues with Gasom, had only served to amplify the discourse surrounding the legislation.

LineNo: 2624211,

Deivid Wisci: I appreciate your understanding, M...
en


"I appreciate your understanding, Mr. President. It's high time we addressed these pressing matters regarding the EPA."

LineNo: 2624313,

Deivid Wisci: “I'm relieved to hear that, Anton.”
en


“I'm relieved to hear that, Anton.”

LineNo: 2624415,

Deivid Wisci: “Thank you, Mr. President.”
en


“Thank you, Mr. President.”

LineNo: 2624517,

Deivid Wisci: I depart earlier for my appointmen...
en


"I depart earlier for my appointments nowadays, as the stairs of the capital have become more of a challenge than I would like to admit."

LineNo: 2624643,

Player: Your wisdom rings true. It's been...
en


"Your wisdom rings true. It's been quite a rollercoaster since the election, hasn't it?"

LineNo: 2624745,

Player: Rest assured, Mr. Wisci. I intend...
en


"Rest assured, Mr. Wisci. I intend to navigate these challenges with more finesse than my predecessors."

LineNo: 2624847,

Player: “The Maroon District and the minist...
en


“The Maroon District and the ministerial buildings are dispersed in a very artificial way. No wonder it takes longer.”

LineNo: 2624949,

Player: “It's nothing to be ashamed of, Dei...
en


“It's nothing to be ashamed of, Deivid. Would you like some coffee or tea?”

LineNo: 2625051,

Player: Well, Deivid, it's not the stairs...
en


"Well, Deivid, it's not the stairs we're battling, but the relentless march of time."

LineNo: 2625153,

Deivid Wisci: I've already had my tea today, as...
en


"I've already had my tea today, as per my doctor's advice. She suggests chamomile in the morning and sage tea in the evening for optimal health."

LineNo: 2625255,

Deivid Wisci: Reflecting on the years I've spent...
en


"Reflecting on the years I've spent within these walls is a journey in itself. From the time my father first brought me here during the reign of the King, right up to the present."

LineNo: 2625357,

Deivid Wisci: It wasn't always like this, you kn...
en


"It wasn't always like this, you know. Before Tarquin Soll and his architect Herman Equa gave this area a neo-classical facelift and a new name, it used to be known as the Republic District. "

LineNo: 2625459,

Deivid Wisci: “I will support you to the end of y...
en


“I will support you to the end of your term and beyond if my health allows.”

LineNo: 2625569,

Deivid Wisci: I trust you're faring well. Sordla...
en


"I trust you're faring well. Sordland is akin to a wild mustang — complex, spirited, and ever elusive to rein in."

LineNo: 2625695,

Player: Or perhaps a stubborn mountain goa...
en


"Or perhaps a stubborn mountain goat, unbudging and headstrong."

LineNo: 2625797,

Deivid Wisci: A public servant is bound by one p...
en


"A public servant is bound by one principle alone. To serve, to be the voice and hand of the people."

LineNo: 2625899,

Deivid Wisci: Listening to the doctor does bring...
en


"Listening to the doctor does bring me some comfort. It feels as though my throat has been refreshed thanks to her."

LineNo: 2626001,

Narrator: A colossal zeppelin traversed the s...
en


A colossal zeppelin traversed the sky above the Maroon District. For a fleeting moment, it blotted out the sun before gently veering to the left, letting light flood the office once more.

LineNo: 2626381,

Deivid Wisci: “I will do my best to support you t...
en


“I will do my best to support you to the end of your term. This country deserves a fresh start and not a descent into the darkness of the distant past.”

LineNo: 2626491,

Deivid Wisci: I often ponder what will endure of...
en


"I often ponder what will endure of our actions and identities. Do they hold any significance in the grand scheme of things?"

LineNo: 2626593,

Narrator: His gaze drifted, locking onto some...
en


His gaze drifted, locking onto something beyond the window.

LineNo: 2626695,

Deivid Wisci: I recall those days with such clar...
en


"I recall those days with such clarity. The city was a vision of beauty, its people radiant with hope. But the civil war shattered our Sordish Dream, exposing the darkest parts of our nature."

LineNo: 2626797,

Deivid Wisci: “My grandmother was a farmer. Throu...
en


“My grandmother was a farmer. Through her, I know that sturdy stubbornness and why the mystical Sordish Mountain Goat is our people's soul animal.”

LineNo: 2626899,

Player: “I need loyal people to make the ch...
en


“I need loyal people to make the change this country deserves.”

LineNo: 2627001,

Player: “The longest roads are travelled ea...
en


“The longest roads are travelled easier with the dearest fellows.”

LineNo: 2627103,

Player: “Your expertise is very welcome in...
en


“Your expertise is very welcome in this administration. People abroad keep praising you.”

LineNo: 2627205,

Narrator: He punctuated his statement with a...
en


He punctuated his statement with a cough, then reached for a glass of water and took a sip.

LineNo: 2627307,

Deivid Wisci: You crossed paths with Herman Equa...
en


"You crossed paths with Herman Equa at Holsord State University, didn't you? He was a mentor to many. I recall our discussions about the future at the Kabaret Lachaven, with him and Heron Garaci."

LineNo: 2627973,

Deivid Wisci: “I know you were just a student at...
en


“I know you were just a student at the Lachaven Business School, far from Holsord. But the armed rebels did reach your area.”

LineNo: 2628083,

Deivid Wisci: “I know you were just a student at...
en


“I know you were just a student at the Deyr University of Culture. Witnessing what true oppression was like.”

LineNo: 2628193,

Deivid Wisci: I did not agree with all of the me...
en


"I did not agree with all of the measures enacted by the technocratic government of that era. But some were undeniably effective."

LineNo: 2628295,

Deivid Wisci: In the end, it took a collective e...
en


"In the end, it took a collective effort to reassemble our nation's fragmented pieces. I'm sure you remember those dark days yourself."

LineNo: 2628397,

Deivid Wisci: A mountain goat, you say? Interest...
en


"A mountain goat, you say? Interesting analogy. They are indeed resilient, much like our nation."

LineNo: 2628499,

Narrator: Just as the conversation hit a paus...
en


Just as the conversation hit a pause, the door swung open and the other ministers arrived. Symon Holl entered first with a confident stride.

LineNo: 2628601,

Symon Holl: Good morning, Mr. President. Deivi...
en


"Good morning, Mr. President. Deivid. I trust the discussion is progressing well?"

LineNo: 2628703,

Narrator: Lileas followed closely behind. She...
en


Lileas followed closely behind. She walked in with an air of calm authority, her gaze sweeping across the room.

LineNo: 2628805,

Lileas Graf: Gentlemen. I hope I'm not interrup...
en


"Gentlemen. I hope I'm not interrupting anything crucial."

LineNo: 2628907,

Player: Still, one must credit Tarquin Sol...
en


"Still, one must credit Tarquin Soll for extricating our nation from the ashes."

LineNo: 2629009,

Player: Perhaps history would have taken a...
en


"Perhaps history would have taken a different course if the Izzam Incident hadn't happened."

LineNo: 2629111,

Player: We are deeply indebted to him. The...
en


"We are deeply indebted to him. The principles of Sollism hold a special place in my heart and continue to guide my decisions."

LineNo: 2629213,

Player_Italic: I kept listening to him.
en


I kept listening to him.

LineNo: 2629219,

Player_Italic: I kept listening to him.
Menu Text en


Keep listening.

LineNo: 2629591,

Player: Those were formative years for me....
en


"Those were formative years for me. Equa and Garaci left an indelible mark on my outlook."

LineNo: 2629693,

Player: It's interesting how those academi...
en


"It's interesting how those academic days shape our perspectives, isn't it?"

LineNo: 2629795,

Player: It was a surreal time, studying bu...
en


"It was a surreal time, studying business principles while chaos ensued just a few miles away."

LineNo: 2629897,

Player: Those disturbances did not deter m...
en


"Those disturbances did not deter me from my studies. In fact, they reinforced the importance of my education."

LineNo: 2629999,

Player: It was a difficult period. But it...
en


"It was a difficult period. But it was also a reminder of the change I wished to see in Sordland."

LineNo: 2630101,

Player: Those experiences have shaped me,...
en


"Those experiences have shaped me, and they continue to inform my decisions as president."

LineNo: 2630203,

Player: In retrospect, an earlier resignat...
en


"In retrospect, an earlier resignation might have been beneficial. His ingrained traditions seem to have done more harm than good in the long run."

LineNo: 2630305,

Deivid Wisci: Indeed, the Izzam Incident is a re...
en


"Indeed, the Izzam Incident is a reminder of how unforeseen events can rapidly change the course of a nation."

LineNo: 2630407,

Deivid Wisci: No one can deny Soll's contributio...
en


"No one can deny Soll's contribution. His leadership was instrumental in rebuilding Sordland."

LineNo: 2630509,

Deivid Wisci: There's merit to that argument. Th...
en


"There's merit to that argument. The lingering influence of Soll's traditions may have hampered Alphonso's ability to bring about the changes he envisioned."

LineNo: 2630611,

Deivid Wisci: Sollism indeed has its virtues, an...
en


"Sollism indeed has its virtues, and it's clear that Soll's legacy continues to resonate with many. The challenge for us is to learn from the past while forging our own path forward."

LineNo: 2630713,

Deivid Wisci: It turned us away from the path of...
en


"It turned us away from the path of reform, but we still worked hard to create the Sordland my father had envisioned."

LineNo: 2630815,

Deivid Wisci: Ah. I still remember the first air...
en


"Ah. I still remember the first airships in Sordland. We purchased them from Qinal after the war, during the birth of what Soll called the 'Second Republic'."

LineNo: 2630917,

Deivid Wisci: Our infrastructure lay in ruins, a...
en


"Our infrastructure lay in ruins, and those zeppelins offered a much-needed lifeline, a chance to traverse and rebuild. And then, thanks to our research council's diligent efforts, we started manufacturing our own in Gelsord."

LineNo: 2631035,

Player: It's fascinating to think how much...
en


"It's fascinating to think how much we depended on foreign help after the war. We've come a long way since then."

LineNo: 2631137,

Player: The manufacturing of zeppelins in...
en


"The manufacturing of zeppelins in Gelsord was truly a turning point."

LineNo: 2631239,

Player: Do you think we might have leaned...
en


"Do you think we might have leaned too heavily on zeppelins for our transportation needs? Perhaps we should have invested more in rebuilding our roads and railways."

LineNo: 2631341,

Deivid Wisci: We were in a desperate state then....
en


"We were in a desperate state then. But remember, it is often in our darkest hours that we find the strength to rise again."

LineNo: 2631443,

Deivid Wisci: You're quite right. It symbolized...
en


"You're quite right. It symbolized our resilience, our determination to regain our footing. It was a beacon of hope, signaling the revival of our battered industry."

LineNo: 2631545,

Deivid Wisci: An interesting point. Perhaps a mo...
en


"An interesting point. Perhaps a more balanced approach would have served us better. In the aftermath of the civil war, it was often about immediate solutions, and the zeppelins offered just that."

LineNo: 2631925,

Deivid Wisci: At the time, the destroyed roads,...
en


"At the time, the destroyed roads, bridges and all made air travel the most suitable option. But now I am glad that your presidency is focusing on building up our infrastructure."

LineNo: 2632027,

Deivid Wisci: But over time, he drifted away fro...
en


"But over time, he drifted away from the ideals of reform and progress that my father held so dear."

LineNo: 2632129,

Deivid Wisci: Our reliance on others was tempora...
en


"Our reliance on others was temporary, a stepping stone towards the self-sufficiency we achieved with the National Autarky Plan. Even though it had downsides, I still consider it a success."

LineNo: 2632231,

Narrator: A pause fell over the room. Deivid'...
en


A pause fell over the room. Deivid's gaze landed on the portrait of Tarquin Soll hanging in the Presidential Office.

LineNo: 2632333,

Player: Those same amendments also opened...
en


"Those same amendments also opened the door to corruption."

LineNo: 2632435,

Player: Do you think the EPA still holds r...
en


"Do you think the EPA still holds relevance today, or should we consider a complete overhaul?"

LineNo: 2632537,

Player: The NAP was a cornerstone for our...
en


"The NAP was a cornerstone for our post-war recovery. I wonder, could we have done more with it?"

LineNo: 2632639,

Deivid Wisci: Hindsight, as they say. We did wha...
en


"Hindsight, as they say. We did what we believed was best at the time. Could we have done more? Perhaps."

LineNo: 2632741,

Deivid Wisci: Indeed, no policy is immune to mis...
en


"Indeed, no policy is immune to misuse. Alphonso's amendments were ambitious, but they also left room for exploitation. We must remain vigilant against such risks."

LineNo: 2632843,

Deivid Wisci: The EPA has its roots in a differe...
en


"The EPA has its roots in a different era. While some of its principles may still hold, we must not shy away from revising it in light of our current needs and challenges."

LineNo: 2632945,

Narrator: His eyes lingered on the stern face...
en


His eyes lingered on the stern face of the old leader. A sigh escaped his lips.

LineNo: 2633047,

Deivid Wisci: Now, when I think of the EPA, my m...
en


"Now, when I think of the EPA, my mind is carried back to the formative years of post-civil war Holsord in the 1930s. The debates, the passion, the potential for transformation—it was a time of renewed optimism."

LineNo: 2633149,

Deivid Wisci: It is our duty now to learn from t...
en


"It is our duty now to learn from the past and strive for a better future. What applied back then won't apply to now."

LineNo: 2633267,

Deivid Wisci: His visionary zeal succumbed to th...
en


"His visionary zeal succumbed to the more pragmatic, more conservative, and sometimes even regressive, dictates of political survival."

LineNo: 2633401,

Player: Life in Holsord back then was toug...
en


"Life in Holsord back then was tough. Electricity blackouts, ruined infrastructure, unemployment, gangs..."

LineNo: 2633503,

Player: I remember that Soll's pardons to...
en


"I remember that Soll's pardons to armed rebels did a lot to quell the rampant unrest."

LineNo: 2633605,

Player: I can see why the Energy Protectio...
en


"I can see why the Energy Protection Act was so crucial at the time. We had to safeguard our energy sector from foreign interference, especially in the context of the post-civil-war economic situation."

LineNo: 2633707,

Deivid Wisci: It was a challenging period, yes,...
en


"It was a challenging period, yes, but we persevered together as a nation."

LineNo: 2633809,

Deivid Wisci: Soll's pardons were undoubtedly a...
en


"Soll's pardons were undoubtedly a contentious move, as they sparked debates about the extent of amnesty granted and the implications for justice."

LineNo: 2633911,

Deivid Wisci: Yes, the EPA helped ensure that th...
en


"Yes, the EPA helped ensure that the sector remained under our control, limiting the extent of ownership of foreign powers such as Rumburg or Lespia."

LineNo: 2634013,

Deivid Wisci: In a way, Tarquin Soll did carry o...
en


"In a way, Tarquin Soll did carry on my father's legacy. Under his leadership, we transitioned from a military government to a civilian one, and experienced our first multi-party elections."

LineNo: 2634115,

Deivid Wisci: “I am sure at least some of my wrin...
en


“I am sure at least some of my wrinkles today were a direct result of my non-stop debates with them.”

LineNo: 2634217,

Deivid Wisci: “Stability and order is important t...
en


“Stability and order is important to our nation. Yet sometimes disorder is necessary for change."

LineNo: 2634319,

Deivid Wisci: “The minorities of this nation have...
en


“The minorities of this nation have suffered particularly.”

LineNo: 2634421,

Deivid Wisci: My father was a visionary, a man w...
en


"My father was a visionary, a man who sought to modernize Sordland into a secular, democratic republic. I've always been guided by his principles."

LineNo: 2634523,

Player: Your father's legacy still looms l...
en


"Your father's legacy still looms large. Has it influenced your own views?"

LineNo: 2634625,

Narrator: Deivid turned towards the large, fr...
en


Deivid turned towards the large, framed portrait of his father, Artor Sanaco Wisci, hanging on the wall. Painted with rich, warm hues, it captured the first President of Sordland in his prime.

LineNo: 2634727,

Narrator: A spark of determination gleamed in...
en


A spark of determination gleamed in his eyes, and his mouth was set in a gentle, firm smile – a reflection of his belief in a better future for our country.

LineNo: 2634845,

Deivid Wisci: His ability to mobilize public sup...
en


"His ability to mobilize public support for revolutionary change has been a constant inspiration to me."

LineNo: 2634947,

Player: Sordland wouldn't be what it is to...
en


"Sordland wouldn't be what it is today without your father."

LineNo: 2635049,

Deivid Wisci: Yes, my father's leadership laid t...
en


"Yes, my father's leadership laid the foundation for the Sordland we know. His policies were aimed at building a secular and democratic state where every citizen's rights are protected."

LineNo: 2635151,

Deivid Wisci: He believed in a Sordland that was...
en


"He believed in a Sordland that was modern and forward-looking. Everything he did was aimed at fostering progress, even his controversial embrace of foreign ideologies."

LineNo: 2635253,

Player: Artor S. Wisci. It's a shame that...
en


"Artor S. Wisci. It's a shame that such an influential man died under such tragic circumstances."

LineNo: 2635355,

Deivid Wisci: Losing my father in the Holsord Pr...
en


"Losing my father in the Holsord Prison fire was a turning point in my life. I was shocked when he was arrested, and his sudden death left a deep void."

LineNo: 2635457,

Deivid Wisci: But it also ignited a fire in me,...
en


"But it also ignited a fire in me, a resolve to carry on his legacy and fight for the principles he stood for. The circumstances of his death are a stark reminder of the lengths to which those in power can go to silence dissent."

LineNo: 2635559,

Narrator: He looked back at the portrait with...
en


He looked back at the portrait with a mix of pride and sadness.

LineNo: 2635661,

Deivid Wisci: It has made me wary, but also more...
en


"It has made me wary, but also more committed to ensuring that such a tragedy does not repeat itself in our country."

LineNo: 2635763,

Deivid Wisci: Alphonso, for all his flaws, did s...
en


"Alphonso, for all his flaws, did seek to set the nation back on a path of progress with his focus on a free market and economic liberalization."

LineNo: 2635865,

Deivid Wisci: His EPA amendments, for example, w...
en


"His EPA amendments, for example, were a severe departure from Soll's National Autarky Plan. But many praised the way that it opened the doors for unprecedented foreign investment in our energy economy."

LineNo: 2635999,

Deivid Wisci: Welcome, everyone. It's great to s...
en


"Welcome, everyone. It's great to see you all here. We have some important discussions on the agenda today, particularly concerning the Energy Protection Act."

LineNo: 2636117,

Player: Thank you, Deivid. I appreciate th...
en


"Thank you, Deivid. I appreciate the urgency. Let's get right to the heart of the matter."

LineNo: 2636219,

Player: Indeed, it's a critical issue that...
en


"Indeed, it's a critical issue that we need to address. I look forward to hearing everyone's perspectives."

LineNo: 2636321,

Player: Proceed.
en


"Proceed."

LineNo: 2636423,

Lileas Graf: The Assembly has spoken on this ma...
en


"The Assembly has spoken on this matter, and as it stands, the Energy Protection Act of 1932 will not be repealed. It's clear that our colleagues have recognized the potential risks of exposing our energy sector to foreign ownership."

LineNo: 2636525,

Lileas Graf: While this doesn't end the debate,...
en


"While this doesn't end the debate, it does underline the importance of respecting our Assembly's decision."

LineNo: 2636651,

Symon Holl: Today, we have the opportunity to...
en


"Today, we have the opportunity to shape the economic strategy of Sordland for decades to come. The EPA has long stood as a key contention and debate point of the National Autarky Plan."

LineNo: 2636753,

Symon Holl: This matter is a discussion of how...
en


"This matter is a discussion of how Sordland sees itself and how we position ourselves in the world. Our nation has taken very different economic approaches in the last four decades."

LineNo: 2637133,

Symon Holl: The President's decision to foster...
en


"The President's decision to foster a planned economy provides us with significant insight into our policy direction."

LineNo: 2637235,

Symon Holl: Mr. President has decided to lean...
en


"Mr. President has decided to lean on promoting a market economy, which should give us a clear indicator."

LineNo: 2637337,

Deivid Wisci: I respect the decision of the Asse...
en


"I respect the decision of the Assembly, Lileas. However, we mustn't allow this setback to deter us from exploring the best possible options for Sordland. The global landscape is ever-evolving and we must adapt accordingly."

LineNo: 2637439,

Symon Holl: It's also important to remember th...
en


"It's also important to remember that the Assembly's decision is not the final word. There is room for further legislative efforts and executive initiatives."

LineNo: 2637541,

Player: A fair point, Lileas. We must resp...
en


"A fair point, Lileas. We must respect the decision of the Assembly, even if it doesn't align with our own views."

LineNo: 2637643,

Player: The Assembly's decision has been m...
en


"The Assembly's decision has been made, but that doesn't mean we will stop advocating for what we believe is right for Sordland."

LineNo: 2637745,

Player: It's disappointing to see the Asse...
en


"It's disappointing to see the Assembly resist change this much. Our debate is definitely not over."

LineNo: 2637847,

Symon Holl: When it comes to the Energy Protec...
en


"When it comes to the Energy Protection Act, I believe we should consider complete removal. If not, at the very least, we should increase the threshold to 49 percent."

LineNo: 2637949,

Symon Holl: This would undoubtedly attract mor...
en


"This would undoubtedly attract more foreign investment and strengthen energy institutions such as Gasom and Sordish Petroleum."

LineNo: 2638051,

Lileas Graf: I'm sure you're right about that....
en


"I'm sure you're right about that. But we have to remember that we're dealing with national security as well as economics. Reverting to the Soll-era 10 percent limit or keeping the law as it is would be a safer approach."

LineNo: 2638153,

Lileas Graf: We cannot risk our energy infrastr...
en


"We cannot risk our energy infrastructure falling into foreign hands. Especially not to Rumburg!"

LineNo: 2638255,

Deivid Wisci: I see merit in both your arguments...
en


"I see merit in both your arguments. Yes, we need to protect our national security, but we also need to consider the economic implications. Perhaps a mixed approach would work best?"

LineNo: 2638357,

Deivid Wisci: What if we increased the limit to...
en


"What if we increased the limit to 49 percent, thereby attracting foreign investment while maintaining Sordish control over critical energy sectors?"

LineNo: 2638459,

Player: Considering potential foreign buye...
en


"Considering potential foreign buyers such as Qinal, Rizia, Anraka, Rumburg, and Lespia, what are the worst-case scenarios if they gain control over our hydroelectric, gas, and oil sectors?"

LineNo: 2638561,

Player: How would the Energy Protection Ac...
en


"How would the Energy Protection Act changes impact corporations like Gasom, which could sell to any entity under the revised laws?"

LineNo: 2638663,

Player: Lileas, you mentioned national sec...
en


"Lileas, you mentioned national security risks. Could you elaborate further on that?"

LineNo: 2638765,

Player: How would changes to the Energy Pr...
en


"How would changes to the Energy Protection Act affect energy prices within Sordland?"

LineNo: 2638867,

Symon Holl: The scenarios Lileas mentioned are...
en


"The scenarios Lileas mentioned are possible, of course, but think about the economic growth and international relations that could be fostered."

LineNo: 2638969,

Lileas Graf: I believe you already know the ans...
en


"I believe you already know the answer to this, Mr. President."

LineNo: 2639071,

Deivid Wisci: There's no denying the potential r...
en


"There's no denying the potential risks of foreign buyers gaining control over critical sectors."

LineNo: 2639173,

Deivid Wisci: National security risks are always...
en


"National security risks are always a concern when discussing foreign ownership. That's why it's crucial to have thorough vetting and monitoring processes in place."

LineNo: 2639275,

Deivid Wisci: With increased foreign investment,...
en


"With increased foreign investment, we could potentially see a decrease in energy prices."

LineNo: 2639377,

Lileas Graf: The national security risks are si...
en


"The national security risks are significant. Foreign entities could use their stake in our energy sector as leverage in diplomatic or economic negotiations."

LineNo: 2639479,

Symon Holl: Yes, Gasom could potentially sell...
en


"Yes, Gasom could potentially sell to anyone, but wouldn't that be a testament to the strength and attractiveness of our energy sector on the global stage?"

LineNo: 2639581,

Lileas Graf: Changing the Energy Protection Act...
en


"Changing the Energy Protection Act could lead to increased energy prices, as foreign entities could manipulate the market."

LineNo: 2639683,

Symon Holl: With increased competition and for...
en


"With increased competition and foreign investment, we could also see a decrease in energy prices. The more players in the market, the more competitive the prices will be."

LineNo: 2639785,

Lileas Graf: I firmly believe in the sovereignt...
en


"I firmly believe in the sovereignty and strength of our nation."

LineNo: 2639887,

Deivid Wisci: Given the turbulent economic lands...
en
